{"id":11,"date":"2023-06-23T18:30:43","date_gmt":"2023-06-23T18:30:43","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/storybook.spectator.co.uk\/?p=11"},"modified":"2023-07-18T16:05:35","modified_gmt":"2023-07-18T16:05:35","slug":"titan-sub-implosion-as-quick-as-turning-on-the-light-switch-what-happened","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/storybook.spectator.co.uk\/news\/titan-sub-implosion-as-quick-as-turning-on-the-light-switch-what-happened\/","title":{"rendered":"Titan sub implosion as quick as \u2018turning on the light switch.\u2019 What happened?"},"content":{"rendered":"<p>Investigators are turning their attention to finding out how a submersible carrying five people to the\u00a0Titanic\u00a0wreckage\u00a0suddenly imploded.<\/p>\n<p><img decoding=\"async\" src=\"https:\/\/d21y75miwcfqoq.cloudfront.net\/70c8fc80\" alt=\"\" \/><\/p>\n<p>All hopes for a positive outcome vanished Thursday when the U.S. <a href=\"https:\/\/messi.online.mills.edu\/\">Coast Guard confirmed<\/a> it found debris belonging to OceanGate Expedition\u2019s Titan near the famous ocean liner at the bottom of the North Atlantic.<\/p>\n<p>The submersible\u2019s disappearance Sunday set off an international rescue mission that captivated the world\u2019s attention given its link to the Titanic. As well,\u00a0the five passengers aboard the Titan\u00a0were reported to have 96 hours of breathable air \u2013 an added element that led to the frantic search.<\/p>\n<div class=\"l-article__part\" data-shortcode=\"tp_video\">\n<div class=\"c-video c-videoPlay \" data-iframe-receiver=\"\" data-autoplay=\"\" data-displayinline-featured=\"false\" data-displayinline-type=\"video\" data-displayinline-player-id=\"miniplayer_9788172_6495e30bcfed4\" data-displayinline-video-id=\"9788172\" data-displayinline-ratio=\"16:9\" data-displayinline=\"https:\/\/globalnews.ca\/video\/embed\/9788172\/#autoplay&amp;stickyiframe=miniplayer_9788172_6495e30bcfed4\" data-displayinline-sticky=\"true\" data-displayinline-listener-i-d=\"0\">\n<div class=\"c-video__inner\">\n<p><span class=\"c-video__placeholder\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" class=\"c-video__image\" src=\"https:\/\/i2.wp.com\/media.globalnews.ca\/videostatic\/news\/4f7smhtor1-r0p4s07g3e\/230622-DAWNA.jpg?w=1040&amp;quality=70&amp;strip=all\" sizes=\"(min-width: 1040px) 1040px,(min-width: 720px) 720px,450px\" srcset=\"https:\/\/i2.wp.com\/media.globalnews.ca\/videostatic\/news\/4f7smhtor1-r0p4s07g3e\/230622-DAWNA.jpg?w=450#038;quality=70&amp;strip=all 450w,https:\/\/i2.wp.com\/media.globalnews.ca\/videostatic\/news\/4f7smhtor1-r0p4s07g3e\/230622-DAWNA.jpg?w=720#038;quality=70&amp;strip=all 720w,https:\/\/i2.wp.com\/media.globalnews.ca\/videostatic\/news\/4f7smhtor1-r0p4s07g3e\/230622-DAWNA.jpg?w=1040#038;quality=70&amp;strip=all 1040w,\" alt=\"Click to play video: 'Experts warned Titan submersible didn\u2019t follow industry safety standards'\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" data-src=\"https:\/\/i2.wp.com\/media.globalnews.ca\/videostatic\/news\/4f7smhtor1-r0p4s07g3e\/230622-DAWNA.jpg?w=1040&amp;quality=70&amp;strip=all\" data-srcset=\"https:\/\/i2.wp.com\/media.globalnews.ca\/videostatic\/news\/4f7smhtor1-r0p4s07g3e\/230622-DAWNA.jpg?w=450#038;quality=70&amp;strip=all 450w,https:\/\/i2.wp.com\/media.globalnews.ca\/videostatic\/news\/4f7smhtor1-r0p4s07g3e\/230622-DAWNA.jpg?w=720#038;quality=70&amp;strip=all 720w,https:\/\/i2.wp.com\/media.globalnews.ca\/videostatic\/news\/4f7smhtor1-r0p4s07g3e\/230622-DAWNA.jpg?w=1040#038;quality=70&amp;strip=all 1040w,\" data-sizes=\"(min-width: 1040px) 1040px,(min-width: 720px) 720px,450px\" data-loaded=\"true\" \/><\/span><\/p>\n<div class=\"c-button c-video__icon c-videoPlay__icon c-button--mini\"><\/div>\n<div class=\"c-video__data\"><time class=\"c-video__duration\">4:02<\/time><span class=\"c-video__title\">Experts warned Titan submersible didn\u2019t follow industry safety standards<\/span><\/div>\n<\/div>\n<\/div>\n<\/div>\n<p>With its unfortunate demise and the death of those on board, investigators are focusing on how the Titan suffered a \u201ccatastrophic implosion,\u201d as it was described Thursday by the U.S. Coast Guard.<\/p>\n<div class=\"c-ad c-ad--bigbox l-article__ad\"><\/div>\n<div class=\"l-article__part\" data-shortcode=\"section-heading\">\n<div class=\"l-article__sectionHeading c-sectionHeading \">\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<h2 class=\"c-sectionHeading__title\">What is an implosion?<\/h2>\n<\/div>\n<\/div>\n<p>First off, an implosion is a process in which objects are destroyed by collapsing on themselves.<\/p>\n<p>It is the opposite of explosion, which is a rapid expansion in volume associated with an extreme outward release of energy.<\/p>\n<p>\u201cThe implosion of the hull means the water pressure was greater than the strength of the material,\u201d said Will Kohnen,<em>\u00a0<\/em>president and CEO of submarine manufacturer Hydra Space Group, and chair of the Marine Technology Society\u2019s manned underwater vehicles committee.<\/p>\n<p>\u201cWhen you reach the point where it doesn\u2019t go anymore, all that stored energy goes into it and that\u2019s what creates the inverse explosion, i.e., implosion, and it happens very fast.\u201d<\/p>\n<div class=\"l-article__part\" data-shortcode=\"tp_video\">\n<div class=\"c-video c-videoPlay \" data-iframe-receiver=\"\" data-autoplay=\"\" data-displayinline-featured=\"false\" data-displayinline-type=\"video\" data-displayinline-player-id=\"miniplayer_9788171_6495e30bd05cb\" data-displayinline-video-id=\"9788171\" data-displayinline-ratio=\"16:9\" data-displayinline=\"https:\/\/globalnews.ca\/video\/embed\/9788171\/#autoplay&amp;stickyiframe=miniplayer_9788171_6495e30bd05cb\" data-displayinline-sticky=\"true\" data-displayinline-listener-i-d=\"1\">\n<div class=\"c-video__inner\">\n<p><span class=\"c-video__placeholder\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" class=\"c-video__image\" src=\"https:\/\/i1.wp.com\/media.globalnews.ca\/videostatic\/news\/1iaykwjbtc-79m2abno31\/230622-ERIC.jpg?w=1040&amp;quality=70&amp;strip=all\" sizes=\"(min-width: 1040px) 1040px,(min-width: 720px) 720px,450px\" srcset=\"https:\/\/i1.wp.com\/media.globalnews.ca\/videostatic\/news\/1iaykwjbtc-79m2abno31\/230622-ERIC.jpg?w=450#038;quality=70&amp;strip=all 450w,https:\/\/i1.wp.com\/media.globalnews.ca\/videostatic\/news\/1iaykwjbtc-79m2abno31\/230622-ERIC.jpg?w=720#038;quality=70&amp;strip=all 720w,https:\/\/i1.wp.com\/media.globalnews.ca\/videostatic\/news\/1iaykwjbtc-79m2abno31\/230622-ERIC.jpg?w=1040#038;quality=70&amp;strip=all 1040w,\" alt=\"Click to play video: 'Titanic sub: What could have caused the implosion of the vessel?'\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" data-src=\"https:\/\/i1.wp.com\/media.globalnews.ca\/videostatic\/news\/1iaykwjbtc-79m2abno31\/230622-ERIC.jpg?w=1040&amp;quality=70&amp;strip=all\" data-srcset=\"https:\/\/i1.wp.com\/media.globalnews.ca\/videostatic\/news\/1iaykwjbtc-79m2abno31\/230622-ERIC.jpg?w=450#038;quality=70&amp;strip=all 450w,https:\/\/i1.wp.com\/media.globalnews.ca\/videostatic\/news\/1iaykwjbtc-79m2abno31\/230622-ERIC.jpg?w=720#038;quality=70&amp;strip=all 720w,https:\/\/i1.wp.com\/media.globalnews.ca\/videostatic\/news\/1iaykwjbtc-79m2abno31\/230622-ERIC.jpg?w=1040#038;quality=70&amp;strip=all 1040w,\" data-sizes=\"(min-width: 1040px) 1040px,(min-width: 720px) 720px,450px\" data-loaded=\"true\" \/><\/span><\/p>\n<div class=\"c-button c-video__icon c-videoPlay__icon c-button--mini\"><\/div>\n<div class=\"c-video__data\"><time class=\"c-video__duration\">2:30<\/time><span class=\"c-video__title\">Titanic sub: What could have caused the implosion of the vessel?<\/span><\/div>\n<\/div>\n<\/div>\n<\/div>\n<p>On Sunday, the Titan suddenly lost contact with Canadian research vessel Polar Prince roughly an hour and 45 minutes after it submerged to descend for a view of the Titanic. It takes more than two hours to get to the wreck.<\/p>\n<div class=\"c-ad c-ad--bigbox l-article__ad\">\n<div id=\"gpt-ad-300250-11\" class=\"c-ad__unit c-ad__unit--loaded\" data-ad-pos=\"11\" data-in-view=\"true\" data-ad-initialized=\"true\" data-google-query-id=\"CNnO9NSC2v8CFUhZKwod9psN6Q\" data-load-time=\"1687544905509\" data-width=\"300\" data-height=\"250\">\n<div id=\"google_ads_iframe_\/6872\/shaw.globalnews.ca\/news\/titanic\/9788605_2__container__\"><\/div>\n<\/div>\n<\/div>\n<p>The Titanic sits almost four kilometres below sea level. The U.S. Coast Guard said Thursday that the Titan\u2019s debris had been found roughly 500 metres from the Titanic.<\/p>\n<p>\u201cThe debris field is consistent with a catastrophic implosion of the vessel,\u201d U.S. Coast Guard Rear-Adm. John Mauger told reporters in Boston.<\/p>\n<div class=\"l-article__part\" data-shortcode=\"section-heading\">\n<div class=\"l-article__sectionHeading c-sectionHeading \">\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<h2 class=\"c-sectionHeading__title\">How could the Titan sub implode?<\/h2>\n<\/div>\n<\/div>\n<p>Mauger initially described the Titan\u2019s debris as \u201cconsistent with the catastrophic loss of the pressure chamber.\u201d<\/p>\n<p>Undersea expert Paul Hankin told reporters in Boston that searchers found five pieces of debris, including the nose cone, which was roughly 500 metres from the Titanic\u2019s bow, and the front-end belt of the pressure hull.<\/p>\n<p>The other end of the pressure hull was found in a second, smaller debris field nearby, Hankin added, which \u2026 basically comprised the totality of that pressure vessel.<\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>Investigators are turning their attention to finding out how a submersible carrying five people to the\u00a0Titanic\u00a0wreckage\u00a0suddenly imploded. All hopes for a positive outcome vanished Thursday when the U.S. Coast Guard confirmed it found debris belonging to OceanGate Expedition\u2019s Titan near the famous ocean liner at the bottom of the North Atlantic. The submersible\u2019s disappearance Sunday<\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":1,"featured_media":0,"comment_status":"open","ping_status":"open","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":{"footnotes":""},"categories":[3],"tags":[],"_links":{"self":[{"href":"https:\/\/storybook.spectator.co.uk\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/11"}],"collection":[{"href":"https:\/\/storybook.spectator.co.uk\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts"}],"about":[{"href":"https:\/\/storybook.spectator.co.uk\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/types\/post"}],"author":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/storybook.spectator.co.uk\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/users\/1"}],"replies":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/storybook.spectator.co.uk\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/comments?post=11"}],"version-history":[{"count":2,"href":"https:\/\/storybook.spectator.co.uk\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/11\/revisions"}],"predecessor-version":[{"id":13,"href":"https:\/\/storybook.spectator.co.uk\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/11\/revisions\/13"}],"wp:attachment":[{"href":"https:\/\/storybook.spectator.co.uk\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/media?parent=11"}],"wp:term":[{"taxonomy":"category","embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/storybook.spectator.co.uk\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/categories?post=11"},{"taxonomy":"post_tag","embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/storybook.spectator.co.uk\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/tags?post=11"}],"curies":[{"name":"wp","href":"https:\/\/api.w.org\/{rel}","templated":true}]}}